      "problem asks to fill in the sorry, let's try to find a derivation of `(О“.conj вӢҸ О”.conj) вӢҸ (ПҶ вӢҺ ПҲ) вҶ’ Оҫ`.\n\nWe have:\n1. `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T`\n2. `(О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T`\n3. `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)) вҶ’ Оҫ` is to be derived.\n\nWe can note that `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)) = (О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ)`.\n\nIf we had that `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T` and `(О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T`, we can try to derive that `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)` and `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ вҶ’ Оҫ)` are in `T`. \n\nBut to get `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)`, from `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)`, we need that `О”.conj` implies something that would allow this. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps it's easier to consider that we have `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)`, and we want `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)`. To get this, we would need that `О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ`, which is true since `О”.conj` is an additional conjunct. \n\nBut perhaps not: since `L` is not necessarily classical, we cannot simply do `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҶ’ О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ` and then use `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)`. \n\nBut perhaps `L` is sufficiently strong that it can derive `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)` from `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)`. \n\nIndeed, in any reasonable logic (like intuitionistic or classical), `(A вҶ’ B)` implies `(A вҲ§ C вҶ’ B)`, because `(A вҲ§ C) вҶ’ A`, and then `(A вҶ’ B)` gives `(A вҲ§ C вҶ’ B)` by transitivity.\n\nBut perhaps here, we need the axiom `(A вҶ’ B) вҶ’ (A вҲ§ C вҶ’ B)`, which is not part of the given `L`. \n\nBut perhaps `L` is assumed to satisfy some basic axioms (e.g., that it's a \"logic\" with some basic implication rules), and that derivation can be done within `L`.\n\nIf we assume that `L` has `(A вҶ’ B) вҶ’ (A вҲ§ C вҶ’ B)`, then:\n\nGiven `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T`, we get `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T` because `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҶ’ (О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ)`, and thus `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)` is derivable (by monotonicity of `вҶ’`). Similarly, `(О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T` implies `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲҲ T`.\n\nThen, since `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)) = (О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ)`, if both `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)` and `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ вҶ’ Оҫ)` are in `T`, then their disjunction implies that `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҲЁ О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ) вҶ’ Оҫ` is in `T`, which is `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)) вҶ’ Оҫ`.\n\nBut perhaps `L` has the axiom `(A вҶ’ C) вҶ’ (B вҶ’ C) вҶ’ (A вҲЁ B вҶ’ C)`.\n\nHowever, in the problem statement, the only assumption is that `L` is a `Entailment.F`, which does not specify such axioms. \n\nBut perhaps `L` is assumed to have the axiom `(A вҶ’ C) вҶ’ (B вҶ’ C) вҶ’ (A вҲЁ B вҶ’ C)` because it's in the \"logic\" class (although this is not clear). \n\nAlternatively, perhaps the derivation can be done in a different way, using only that `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҶ’ Оҫ)` and `(О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ вҶ’ Оҫ)` are in `T`, and that `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ))` can be reduced somehow.\n\nBut perhaps it's better to recognize that the statement is not actually needed, and that there is a different way to obtain the contradiction. \n\nBut perhaps the initial approach is not working, and the problem is harder than it appears. \n\nBut since we must fill in the sorry, perhaps we can try to make some assumptions about `L`'s axioms, like it being at least as strong as intuitionistic logic, which has `(A вҶ’ C) вҶ’ (B вҶ’ C) вҶ’ (A вҲЁ B вҶ’ C)`.\n\nBut in Lean, `L` is only given as `Entail",
