      "Hence, `Оҫ` is true.\n3. Case 2: `ПҲ` is true.\n   - Then, `О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ` is true (since `О”.conj` is true).\n   - Hence, `Оҫ` is true.\n\nIn both cases, `Оҫ` is true. \n\nBut in Lean's notation, we're not given that `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj) вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)` is assumed true, but instead:\n1. We have that `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҶ’ Оҫ` and `(О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ) вҶ’ Оҫ`.\n2. We want to derive that `((О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj) вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)) вҶ’ Оҫ`.\n\nBut the structure of the implication is different from what we'd expect. \n\nGiven that Lean's `logic` has `Entailment.F`, we know it to be classical (as `F` means \"full\" cases). \nIn particular, if we have `L`, then perhaps we can just use the law of excluded middle.\n\nHowever, in this case, it is better to directly think of the following implication:\n```\n( (О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҶ’ Оҫ) вҲ§ ( (О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ) вҶ’ Оҫ) вҶ’ ( ( (О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj) вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)) вҶ’ Оҫ )\n```\n\nBut to prove this, we can use the following identity:\n\n`( (О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj) вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ) ) вҶ’ ( (О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ) )`.\n\nThis is because:\n```\n(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj) вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ) = О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ вҲЁ О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ\n= (О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲ§ О”.conj вҲЁ (О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ) вҲ§ О“.conj\nвҮ’ (О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ).\n```\nHere, we need to say that `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲ§ О”.conj` implies `О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ`, and `(О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ) вҲ§ О“.conj` implies `О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ`.\n\nBut actually:\n`(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj) вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)` is not equivalent to `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ)`, but it is equivalent to:\n`(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ)`, which implies `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ)`.\n\nSo, perhaps we need to:\n1. Prove that `(О“.conj вҲ§ О”.conj) вҲ§ (ПҶ вҲЁ ПҲ)` implies `(О“.conj вҲ§ ПҶ) вҲЁ (О”.conj вҲ§ ПҲ)` in `L`.\n2. Use the transitivity of implication to conclude.\n\nThis is actually manageable in a classical logic because it is straightfo